WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.080
My name is Thomas Petersen, I'm a software engineer at Perset, and it is my great pleasure

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:12.780
to welcome the first speaker on stage.

00:00:12.780 --> 00:00:18.559
She is Reiko Okamoto, and she's a methodologist at Brea Research Institute.

00:00:18.559 --> 00:00:24.559
Give her a hand.

00:00:24.559 --> 00:00:31.840
Hi everyone, just going to wait for a few people to trickle in.

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:41.759
Alright, so one of the most important parts of my late childhood and adolescence growing

00:00:41.759 --> 00:00:47.840
up in Canada was reality shows on cable television.

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:54.320
And whether it involved 11 teams of two in a race around the world, or an up-and-coming

00:00:54.320 --> 00:01:00.320
chef fighting against an iron chef based on a secret ingredient, I just could not get

00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:05.800
enough of this unscripted chaos unfolding in front of me.

00:01:05.800 --> 00:01:10.360
And during the early days of the pandemic, when I was spending a questionable amount

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:17.400
of time on YouTube, one day I stumbled down a recommendation of Rabbit Hole and reunited

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:23.400
with another show that I remembered watching growing up called Neat.

00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:29.599
Now Neat was this dramatic makeover series that was on home and garden television in

00:01:29.599 --> 00:01:38.800
which a professional organizer named Helen would help a person or family put cluttered

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:45.519
living spaces, devise solutions to better organize their lives and possessions more

00:01:45.519 --> 00:01:47.320
effectively.

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:53.720
Now as someone with experience performing data analysis in both academia and the public

00:01:53.720 --> 00:02:00.839
sector, I just could not help but to notice that many of the principles of home organization

00:02:00.839 --> 00:02:05.160
are actually applicable to file management.

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:13.000
So for example, whether it's physical or digital, clutter in our space is usually clutter

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:15.600
in our minds as well.

00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:21.559
And more importantly, clutter shouldn't be taking away our focus and creativity, nor

00:02:21.559 --> 00:02:25.160
should it be blocking our way to success.

00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:31.360
That being said, unfortunately, tips about file management can often be presented as

00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:35.759
this mixed bag of ideas without a unifying narrative.

00:02:35.759 --> 00:02:42.759
Or even worse, file management itself can be entirely overlooked in favor of arguably

00:02:42.759 --> 00:02:47.839
more exciting topics like machine learning and data visualization.

00:02:47.839 --> 00:02:55.440
So my goal over the next 15 minutes or so is to draw comparisons between home organization

00:02:55.559 --> 00:03:01.440
and file management to better illustrate that keeping your space clean and tidy is going

00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:05.100
to save you a lot of time down the road.

00:03:05.100 --> 00:03:11.759
So as I was watching these clips uploaded onto YouTube, I noticed that the show often

00:03:11.759 --> 00:03:17.919
featured a client that was struggling to declutter either their living room and dining combo

00:03:17.919 --> 00:03:20.960
or studio apartment.

00:03:20.960 --> 00:03:27.119
Now what was common to these spaces was that without distinct rooms separated by walls,

00:03:27.119 --> 00:03:33.559
boundaries became blurred and as a result, it was really unclear as to where one activity

00:03:33.559 --> 00:03:36.440
ended and another one began.

00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:42.520
For example, I'm talking about a dining table potentially turning into a secondary office

00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:43.520
desk.

00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:45.360
Does that sound familiar?

00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:49.919
Or an overflowing box of business receipts somehow sitting on a kitchen counter.

00:03:49.919 --> 00:03:51.440
Is that familiar as well?

00:03:51.440 --> 00:03:52.440
Not sure.

00:03:52.440 --> 00:03:59.440
But to address this issue, the host would begin by moving existing furniture or adding

00:03:59.440 --> 00:04:05.240
these room dividers to create dedicated spaces that were conducive to a specific activity.

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:10.440
So I'm talking about a space for eating and another space for working.

00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:16.299
And I think the digital analog to this kind of clutter is a documents folder that has

00:04:16.299 --> 00:04:21.899
just become this dumping ground for ad hoc analysis, plots, meeting minutes, and so much

00:04:21.899 --> 00:04:24.220
more.

00:04:24.220 --> 00:04:31.500
And we can begin to address this mess by organizing our work into self-contained projects where

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:36.940
each project is a folder that contains all the files relevant to a particular piece of

00:04:36.940 --> 00:04:37.940
work.

00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:44.019
So this involves the input data, any R scripts, and their associated results.

00:04:44.019 --> 00:04:49.059
And furthermore, any R code that's going to be sitting in this folder, you're going

00:04:49.059 --> 00:04:55.339
to write it as if it will be run from a fresh R session with its working directory pointed

00:04:55.339 --> 00:04:58.700
to the project's root.

00:04:58.700 --> 00:05:05.940
And this method of compartmentalization conveniently allows us to move our project or folder from

00:05:05.940 --> 00:05:13.019
one location on our computer to another or onto an entirely different machine while ensuring

00:05:13.019 --> 00:05:17.299
that the code is most likely going to work in its new location.

00:05:17.299 --> 00:05:25.260
And I think we can further elevate this method of compartmentalization by using RStudio projects.

00:05:25.260 --> 00:05:31.459
So if you're new to RStudio projects, when a new project is created, either in a brand

00:05:31.459 --> 00:05:37.619
new or existing directory, RStudio creates a project file within the directory, which

00:05:37.619 --> 00:05:41.820
is then used to store the settings that are specific to that project.

00:05:41.820 --> 00:05:47.179
So if we ever want to return to the project after taking a small break, we can just open

00:05:47.179 --> 00:05:48.820
up that project file.

00:05:48.820 --> 00:05:56.739
And in the IDE, we'll see that the current working directory is set to the project directory.

00:05:56.739 --> 00:06:01.940
The file browser is pointed at the project folder.

00:06:01.940 --> 00:06:08.140
Any previously edited files are restored into the editor tabs.

00:06:08.140 --> 00:06:14.500
And other RStudio settings, such as active tabs and splitter positions, are going to

00:06:14.500 --> 00:06:22.660
be restored to exactly where they were the last time the project was closed.

00:06:22.660 --> 00:06:29.619
And furthermore, a new R session is started.

00:06:29.619 --> 00:06:35.459
And this aligns with our idea of self-contained projects that we discussed earlier.

00:06:35.459 --> 00:06:41.019
And this setup makes it easier to jump back into a specific analysis after you've taken

00:06:41.019 --> 00:06:47.299
a break from it, or to juggle multiple analyses at once without disorder.

00:06:47.299 --> 00:06:55.140
And to tie this all back to home organization, I think it's similar to how it's a lot easier

00:06:55.140 --> 00:07:00.779
to go from practicing the piano to cooking dinner when you have established dedicated

00:07:00.779 --> 00:07:07.579
spaces for each activity, rather than having to move dirty laundry off of the piano or

00:07:07.579 --> 00:07:13.459
that box of business receipts off of your kitchen counter before doing what it is that

00:07:13.459 --> 00:07:18.980
you actually want to be doing.

00:07:18.980 --> 00:07:25.420
And at some point in each episode on Neat, the host, Helen, often encouraged the clients

00:07:25.420 --> 00:07:33.579
to let go of duplicates and items that they're just holding onto just in case to reduce clutter.

00:07:33.579 --> 00:07:38.579
And understandably, on the show, some people found it challenging to let go of these sentimental

00:07:38.579 --> 00:07:39.579
items.

00:07:39.579 --> 00:07:43.779
You know, this could have been like a preteen refusing to part ways with their collection

00:07:43.779 --> 00:07:51.579
of stuffed animals, or a parent going through outgrown baby clothes and really trying to

00:07:51.579 --> 00:07:55.339
carefully choose an item from each milestone.

00:07:55.339 --> 00:08:01.540
And I think as data analysts, we can cling on to files in a similar fashion, especially

00:08:01.540 --> 00:08:08.380
because data analysis often involves iteration and revision to go from this initial idea

00:08:08.380 --> 00:08:12.540
to the final deliverable.

00:08:12.540 --> 00:08:18.339
And without a good system in place for tracking how something evolves over time, projects

00:08:18.339 --> 00:08:22.299
can easily turn messy, as you see up here.

00:08:22.299 --> 00:08:28.220
And to address this mess, one thing that we can do is to adopt version control.

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:35.539
And this gives us the option to revert selected files back to a previous state, compare changes

00:08:35.539 --> 00:08:42.380
over time, see who modified something and when, all without having to keep every version

00:08:42.380 --> 00:08:50.219
of the file, further reducing the amount of visual clutter that we have on our machines.

00:08:50.219 --> 00:08:54.419
And on the show, once the unnecessary clutter was removed from the home, the host would

00:08:54.419 --> 00:08:59.380
then set up an organizational system that was suited to the client's lifestyle and the

00:08:59.380 --> 00:09:02.500
possessions that they held.

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:09.739
Specifically, when using storage bins, the host, Helen, would make it really easy to

00:09:09.739 --> 00:09:15.260
find things in the future by leaving no doubt as to what was inside each one of these containers.

00:09:15.820 --> 00:09:20.340
So we're talking about using transparent, clear containers or using the label printer

00:09:20.340 --> 00:09:24.260
and printing out a label for each one of these boxes.

00:09:24.260 --> 00:09:30.859
And in a similar fashion, I think as analysts, it's crucial for us to adopt a directory structure

00:09:30.859 --> 00:09:35.900
that matches the type of project that we're working on.

00:09:35.900 --> 00:09:41.739
So for an ad hoc analysis that I have on the left, that might mean creating a subfolder

00:09:41.979 --> 00:09:48.500
for raw data, another one for the code used in the analysis, maybe another one to keep

00:09:48.500 --> 00:09:50.059
the respective outputs.

00:09:50.059 --> 00:09:56.580
Meanwhile, on the right-hand side, for an R package, the package development conventions

00:09:56.580 --> 00:10:01.340
may encourage us to create a subdirectory for function definitions, another one for

00:10:01.340 --> 00:10:05.059
unit tests, another one for vignettes, and so on.

00:10:05.059 --> 00:10:10.940
But regardless of what kind of project we're working on, whether that's ad hoc analyses

00:10:10.979 --> 00:10:18.619
or R package, going back to this idea of leaving no doubt as to what's inside each container,

00:10:18.619 --> 00:10:24.820
we should always consider adding a README to the project route, which tells other people

00:10:24.820 --> 00:10:30.739
why our project is useful, what they can do with it, and how they can use it.

00:10:30.739 --> 00:10:37.020
And if there's a lot of content to squeeze into one README file, I think that invites

00:10:37.020 --> 00:10:44.659
us to consider whether it's appropriate to place additional README files in the subdirectories.

00:10:44.659 --> 00:10:50.099
And speaking from personal experience, at my previous workplace, we had a folder on

00:10:50.099 --> 00:10:58.979
a shared drive that contained many, many, many ad hoc analyses, or many, many RMD files,

00:10:58.979 --> 00:11:04.419
and each file was for a particular piece of ad hoc analysis.

00:11:04.419 --> 00:11:09.539
And a colleague of mine suggested creating a lookup table, which summarized the content

00:11:09.539 --> 00:11:15.460
of each file to make it easier to refer back to the previous analysis when needed.

00:11:15.460 --> 00:11:23.859
So I took her suggestion, and I wrote a code snippet to automatically parse the YAML metadata

00:11:23.859 --> 00:11:29.739
from each RMD file that was sitting in the analysis subdirectory to generate this lookup

00:11:29.739 --> 00:11:38.299
table, which was then embedded into the README file of the analysis subdirectory.

00:11:38.299 --> 00:11:43.659
So here, I'm sharing this reworked version of the code that I just talked about.

00:11:43.659 --> 00:11:48.659
So this is a reworked version of the code for Cordo documents.

00:11:48.659 --> 00:11:56.020
And I'm beginning by defining a function with the help of the Cordo packages, Cordo inspect,

00:11:56.020 --> 00:12:01.340
to retrieve the metadata of interest for a given file.

00:12:01.340 --> 00:12:08.099
And then I map this function that I just defined, extract metadata, to all the QMD files found

00:12:08.099 --> 00:12:13.260
in a given directory, to generate this table that you see on the bottom, that allows me

00:12:13.260 --> 00:12:18.900
to quickly inspect the file name, the title, and the subtitle that's sitting inside the

00:12:18.900 --> 00:12:24.380
YAML metadata component of each Cordo document very quickly.

00:12:24.380 --> 00:12:33.219
And if you want, you can then add this table to the README.md of a particular subdirectory

00:12:33.219 --> 00:12:38.340
that you might want to provide more information on.

00:12:38.340 --> 00:12:43.539
And once again, going back to the show, so once the host helped clear the clutter and

00:12:43.539 --> 00:12:48.739
figured out what kind of organizational system was best suited to the client's lifestyle

00:12:48.739 --> 00:12:54.619
and possessions, she further elevated the space by ensuring consistency.

00:12:54.619 --> 00:13:00.460
And I think a great example of this is using matching hangers to reduce visual clutter

00:13:00.460 --> 00:13:03.900
and to make a closet easier to navigate.

00:13:03.900 --> 00:13:09.659
And this can be a little bit more difficult when you have a mix of metal and plastic hangers,

00:13:09.659 --> 00:13:14.700
and maybe some of those hangers that you get for free from the dry cleaners.

00:13:15.419 --> 00:13:21.820
And in the world of file management, I think this messiness resembles not having a proper

00:13:21.820 --> 00:13:27.099
framework in place for naming our files.

00:13:27.099 --> 00:13:32.419
But through adopting a file naming convention, we can further reduce the amount of visual

00:13:32.419 --> 00:13:38.419
clutter on our machines and also make it easier for us to find things in the future.

00:13:38.419 --> 00:13:43.780
And Jenny Bryan, who is also at this conference, I believe has shared some great resources

00:13:43.780 --> 00:13:45.739
on file naming conventions.

00:13:45.739 --> 00:13:49.859
So for the next little bit, I'm going to be drawing from her expertise, and I'll share

00:13:49.859 --> 00:13:54.099
the three features that constitute a good file name.

00:13:54.099 --> 00:13:59.099
First, a good file name should be machine readable.

00:13:59.099 --> 00:14:06.260
So we're talking about avoiding special characters, avoiding spaces, and also being mindful of

00:14:06.260 --> 00:14:08.059
case sensitivity.

00:14:08.059 --> 00:14:15.900
And this is also that our file names can play well with our machine's inherent search functionality.

00:14:15.900 --> 00:14:21.580
And here I'm focusing on the intentional use of underscores to allow for the easy recovery

00:14:21.580 --> 00:14:28.099
of metadata using glob patterns or regular expressions down the road.

00:14:28.099 --> 00:14:34.340
The second feature of a good file name is that it should be human readable.

00:14:34.340 --> 00:14:39.460
And here I'm using hyphens to delimit words to make the file names a little bit easier

00:14:39.460 --> 00:14:40.460
for us to read.

00:14:40.460 --> 00:14:46.460
And I'm also focusing on using descriptive and non-generic keywords.

00:14:46.460 --> 00:14:51.659
This is so that I can provide somewhat of a preview in terms of the content and purpose

00:14:51.659 --> 00:14:53.140
of the file.

00:14:53.140 --> 00:15:00.859
The third feature is that the file name should allow for the files to be arranged in a useful

00:15:00.859 --> 00:15:04.619
way while assuming alphanumeric ordering.

00:15:04.619 --> 00:15:11.020
So here in the top half of the slide, I'm using the ISO 8601 standard for dates when

00:15:11.020 --> 00:15:15.059
I want my files to be arranged in chronological order.

00:15:15.059 --> 00:15:20.140
And in the bottom half, I'm making sure to left pad the numbers with zero when I want

00:15:20.140 --> 00:15:22.859
my scripts to be in logical order.

00:15:22.859 --> 00:15:27.580
Or the order in which they're called in an analysis workflow.

00:15:27.580 --> 00:15:34.299
And left padding with zero prevents situations like the number 10 written as one zero appearing

00:15:34.299 --> 00:15:37.260
before two in a list.

00:15:37.260 --> 00:15:42.419
Maybe you have experienced that in the past while naming files.

00:15:42.419 --> 00:15:48.900
So we covered a lot of ground, so I think it's a good moment to recap what we've discussed.

00:15:48.900 --> 00:15:55.700
And I hope over the past 15 minutes, I was able to convince you that by applying techniques

00:15:55.700 --> 00:16:03.020
I shared on an home organization show, such as creating dedicated zones, reducing redundancy,

00:16:03.020 --> 00:16:08.619
setting up customized storage solutions, and pursuing visual consistency, you can create

00:16:08.619 --> 00:16:16.500
a serene, relaxing workspace that facilitates reproducible analysis, is inviting to other

00:16:16.500 --> 00:16:21.859
collaborators, including your future self, and exudes professionalism.

00:16:21.859 --> 00:16:28.340
So whether you're an instructor looking to revise their file management lesson plan,

00:16:28.340 --> 00:16:33.460
or maybe you are someone who wants to inspire their colleagues to reconsider file management

00:16:33.460 --> 00:16:39.619
practices in the workplace, I hope this narrative provided you with some inspiration today.

00:16:39.619 --> 00:16:42.739
Thank you for listening, and I hope you enjoy the rest of the conference.

00:16:42.739 --> 00:16:48.419
Thank you so much, Raiko.

00:16:48.419 --> 00:16:51.619
So we'll have time for a few questions.

00:16:51.619 --> 00:16:52.619
First one.

00:16:52.619 --> 00:16:56.380
How do you encourage ongoing good file management?

00:16:56.380 --> 00:17:03.140
One thing that I caught myself doing today, I was trying to upload a copy of this slide

00:17:03.140 --> 00:17:09.420
to my GitHub, and I realized that the default file name for the PDF wasn't so good.

00:17:09.420 --> 00:17:13.819
And I was really tired, because it was like 9 o'clock last night, and I was like, I'll

00:17:13.819 --> 00:17:14.819
just leave it as is.

00:17:14.819 --> 00:17:18.900
But then I kind of thought to myself, I should be a good role model and probably give it

00:17:18.900 --> 00:17:21.099
a better file name.

00:17:21.099 --> 00:17:33.260
So I think it starts by you applying and demonstrating what you are trying to convince your colleagues

00:17:33.260 --> 00:17:38.900
in terms of making them do exactly what it is that you want them to follow.

00:17:38.900 --> 00:17:39.900
Yeah.

00:17:39.900 --> 00:17:40.900
Fantastic.

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:42.180
Another question.

00:17:42.180 --> 00:17:49.819
So in a home, there's a need for a drawer that is messy so that everything else can

00:17:49.819 --> 00:17:52.260
be un-messy.

00:17:52.260 --> 00:17:56.140
Is there a similar idea for files?

00:17:56.140 --> 00:17:57.140
Hmm.

00:17:57.140 --> 00:18:00.939
Like a dumping ground that kind of has to be there.

00:18:00.939 --> 00:18:06.540
Yeah, in the past, I think involuntarily, we've ended up in situations where folders

00:18:06.540 --> 00:18:08.420
like that have existed.

00:18:08.420 --> 00:18:13.859
But then I think you also then have to be responsible for setting up a reasonable timeline

00:18:13.859 --> 00:18:21.859
as to when you want to go back and re-sort, delete things from that dumping ground folder

00:18:21.859 --> 00:18:28.739
to really keep it as a temporary solution as opposed to something that is going to consistently

00:18:28.739 --> 00:18:30.540
live within your team's workspace.

00:18:30.540 --> 00:18:31.540
Fantastic.

00:18:31.540 --> 00:18:32.540
Thank you so much, Raiko.

00:18:32.540 --> 00:18:33.540
Thanks.

00:18:33.540 --> 00:18:33.540


00:18:38.420 --> 00:18:39.420
Thank you.

00:18:39.420 --> 00:18:39.420


